<Author>Traipsers
<Content>Well-run and reliable little place We had no expectations of this hotel before arriving, as we had originally planned to stay at the KK Hotel Cayre in the 6th. Unfortunately, the KK's air conditioning was not working well, and it was 90 degrees the day we arrived. So we ended up moving to the Radisson, and the staff was very friendly and understanding of our situation. They didn't try to gouge us just because they sensed how desperate we were to find other accommodations. They set us up in a room with a view of the Eiffel Tower and the Arc--granted, we could only see the top of the tower, and the arc was visible only if we stuck our heads out our window and looked to the right. But it was still pretty nice.The room--relatively small, but not uncomfortably so, and certainly not unusually small by Paris standards. Also, there was a nice-sized hallway in the room that made it feel more spacious, and a huge full-sized mirror. And we had a terrace with typical large French windows. Yes, the terrace was small and really only big enough to stand in, but the mere fact that it was there made the room feel bigger. The room was always spotless, and turndown service was consistent and on time. The air conditioning was wonderful and individually controlled. TV worked fine, good amount of closet space, and lots of shelves to store your belongings. The bathroom--very cute, and very clean, except for one or two tiny patches of mildew in the shower tile. Otherwise, I only had two minor complaints about the bathroom. First, the sink drain was very, very slow. The sink was also very shallow and did not have a run-off drain, so, basically, in order to avoid overflow, you had to keep the water going at only a trickle. If you let it flow full blast, you basically ended up with a full sink within seconds. Second, the shower door was only about a foot wide, and leaked like crazy. We put three towels down on the floor to absorb the water, but after every shower, the towels and the floor were soaking wet. I mentioned these issues to the front desk. They were very smiling and understood the problems, but said that was just the way the bathrooms were designed. Slightly annoying, but not a huge deal.The service--I found the front desk staff very friendly and eager to please. They did not seem super-knowledgeable about restaurant recommendations and the like, so I wouldn't rely on them for that kind of information. What they are helpful with are calling places for you, lending umbrellas, etc. They always said good morning and good night with a smile, which was nice. The location--super-touristy and super-expensive, with a sprinkling of office buildings and car dealerships. (Mind you, these are Parisian office buildings and car dealerships, which are not ugly eye sores at all; it just means the neighborhood can be pretty dead in spots, especially during the summer.) The outdoor cafes on the Champs Elysees, which are right around the corner from the hotel, are overpriced and mediocre. That said, the hotel is in easy walking distance of just about everything in central Paris. The nearest taxi stand is 2 blocks away, and you can get just about anywhere in 10 minutes. Even Sacre Coeur is only a 15-minute cab ride away. Another convenience: there is an amazing drugstore/gift shop around the corner called Publicis Drugstore. It's pricey, but is great for supplies like bottled water, batteries, toiletries, newspapers, etc., as well as fun non-essentials like purses, cashmere sweaters, and just about anything else you can think of. Overall, the area felt very safe.I would definitely stay at this hotel again and would recommend it to friends. It's not particularly charming or special or glamorous, but it's clean, spotless, friendly, and reasonably priced. 
