<Content>Good location. Nice hotel I hesitated to review this hotel as I was there on points, and sometimes it's not a fair assessment if you're not a paying customer. But I'll add my quick two cents. Location? Could NOT be much better. Of course, depending on what you're looking for. Near the fabulous designers, L'Arc de Triomphe was visible if I leaned out my window, Champs Elysees a 1 minute walk, restaurants, the Metro, a LOVELY store about a 30 second walk that had anything you could possibly need, an epicurean delight. This was my 4th trip to Paris, but each has been very different. This one was luxurious. If you're looking for more flavor/charm/character...the Champs Elysees might not be the area for you. Room was beautiful. Wooden floors and built ins, gorgeous bathroom. I had two rooms (traveling with teens) that connected and both were nice. I was booked in a standard room, but I don't know if they might have upgraded me or not. The rooms were quite large with TONS of closet space. They look like the hotel's website. BUT...on arrival we had no air conditioning. I called down and was told it was inadvertently not turned on from downstairs, and that they then did so. I struggled for the next 2 nights wondering why it was still sweltering, but felt uncomfortable asking again because they SAID they'd corrrected it. Fortunately, it was COLD outside, so the rooms never got so that we couldn't stand it, but it was close. There was no opening the window to cool the room beause they were fabulously soundproofing. But, if you opened them, there is an underground garage entrance just outside the hotel and the horrid loud noise of cars exiting/entering and going over a metal plate is constant. The last day, I finally asked again, they said they'd call me back. In 5 minutes the air started and they never did call me back. We could hardly sleep so this was the only REALLY disappointing part. We ate the full breakfast there both days, and it was reasonably priced compared to others. And it was VERY good. The service was polite at the small restaurant/bar...as well as the front desk. I got a tiny bit of attitude from the concierge when I asked if they could check when the Paris Opera (Garnier) held tours in English. My daughter is a huge fan and, though we speak a bit of French, knew we'd get a lot more out of the tour in English. But online searches gave conflicting information and it was THE reason we decided to stop in Paris again. Well, I've never done anything like that...but I guess I'll make the call. Of course I tipped him, and ... in typical American fashion overtipped. But he still must have felt it was something he shouldn't have to do. 
